================================================================
SCOPY - Smart Copy for CP/M 2.2
Specification Document
Version 1.0 — April 2026
================================================================

1. OVERVIEW
----------------------------------------------------------------

SCOPY is a file copy utility for CP/M 2.2 that supports
copying files across drives, across user areas, and within
the same drive and user area (with rename). It replaces PIP
for file copy operations with an intuitive left-to-right
syntax and full user area support.

Target platform:  CP/M 2.2 (IMSAI 8080)
Toolchain:        Microsoft M80 Macro Assembler / L80 Linker
Output:           SCOPY.COM (transient command, loaded at 0100H)


2. COMMAND LINE SYNTAX
----------------------------------------------------------------

  SCOPY source destination [/options]

Source and destination are file specifications in the form:

  [user]drive:filename.ext

All parts are optional with sensible defaults:

  [user]  — User area 0-15 in brackets. Default: current user.
  drive:  — Drive letter A-P followed by colon. Default: current drive.
  filename.ext — Filename (1-8 chars) and extension (0-3 chars).
                 Wildcards * and ? are supported in source only.

The special destination "." means the current drive and current
user area.

2.1. Examples

  SCOPY FILE.COM B:              Current user, current drive to B:
  SCOPY B:FILE.COM .             B: to current drive, same user
  SCOPY [3]FILE.COM [5]B:        User 3 current drive to user 5 B:
  SCOPY [0]A:*.COM [3]B:         User 0 A: all .COM to user 3 B:
  SCOPY *.ASM [2]                Current drive to user 2, same drive
  SCOPY [4]B:README.ME .         User 4 B: to current user/drive
  SCOPY FOO.COM B:BAR.COM        Copy and rename (single file only)

2.2. Option Flags

  /V  — Verify after copy (read-back compare of each file)
  /C  — Confirm each file before copying (Y/N prompt)
  /R  — Replace existing files without prompting
  /Q  — Quiet mode, suppress per-file output

Multiple flags may be combined: /VC or /V /C

Default behavior (no flags):
  - Show each filename as it is copied
  - Prompt before overwriting an existing file
  - No verify pass


3. TAB FILENAME COMPLETION
----------------------------------------------------------------

SCOPY provides interactive filename completion using the TAB
key. Since the CCP command tail is already parsed before SCOPY
runs, TAB completion is available when SCOPY prompts for input
interactively. This occurs when:

  - SCOPY is run with no arguments — it prompts for source
    and destination separately.
  - SCOPY is run with only a source — it prompts for the
    destination.

3.1. Interactive Prompts

  When arguments are missing, SCOPY prompts:

    Source: _
    Dest:   _

  The user types a partial file specification and presses TAB
  to trigger completion. The full command line editing keys
  are available: backspace to delete, CTRL-C to abort, and
  RETURN to accept the current input.

3.2. Completion Behavior

  As the user types a partial file specification such as:

    Source: [2]B:AS

  Pressing TAB triggers the following:

  1. Parse the partial input to extract the user area, drive,
     and partial filename.
  2. Set the specified user area (or current user if omitted).
  3. Select the specified drive (or current drive if omitted).
  4. Build an ambiguous FCB from the partial input by padding
     the partial filename with "?" characters.
     Example: "AS" becomes "AS??????.???"
  5. Search the directory using BDOS functions 17/18 (Search
     First / Search Next) to find all matching filenames.
  6. Display the first matching filename, replacing the
     partial text on the console line.
     Example: the line becomes "Source: [2]B:ASM.COM"
  7. Each subsequent TAB press cycles to the next matching
     filename in directory order.
  8. After the last match, the next TAB wraps back to the
     first match (circular cycling).
  9. If no filenames match the partial input, send BEL (07H)
     to ring the terminal bell. The partial input is left
     unchanged.

3.3. Console Line Editing for Completion

  When a completion is displayed, the partial text is erased
  from the console and replaced with the full filename:

  1. Send backspace (08H), space (20H), backspace (08H) for
     each character of the currently displayed filename or
     partial text to erase it visually.
  2. Print the new completed filename.
  3. The cursor is positioned after the completed filename,
     ready for the user to press RETURN to accept or TAB
     to cycle.

3.4. Completion with User/Drive Prefix

  The user area and drive prefix are NOT erased during TAB
  cycling — only the filename.ext portion is replaced.

    Source: [2]B:ASM.COM     (TAB)
    Source: [2]B:ASSIGN.COM  (TAB)
    Source: [2]B:ASM.COM     (wraps around)

3.5. Wildcards and Completion

  TAB completion and wildcards are complementary:
  - The user may type a partial name, TAB to complete it,
    then manually edit to add wildcards before pressing
    RETURN.
  - TAB does not expand wildcards — it searches the directory
    for matching names.
  - If the user has already typed a wildcard character (* or
    ?) in the partial input, TAB is ignored (bell sounds).

3.6. Implementation Notes

  - The completion match list is rebuilt on each first TAB
    press after typing. Subsequent TABs cycle through the
    cached list.
  - The match list is stored in a small buffer. If more than
    64 filenames match, only the first 64 are available for
    cycling.
  - Pressing any character other than TAB after a completion
    clears the match list. The next TAB will rebuild it.
  - BDOS function 6 (Direct Console I/O) is used for
    character-by-character input to intercept TAB (09H)
    before the BDOS line editor processes it.
  - Restore the original user area and drive after the
    directory search, before prompting for more input.


4. HELP SCREEN
----------------------------------------------------------------

Running SCOPY /? displays the help screen. Running SCOPY with
no arguments enters interactive mode with TAB completion
(see section 3).

  SCOPY v1.0 - Smart Copy for CP/M 2.2

  Usage: SCOPY source destination [/options]
         SCOPY [/options]  (interactive with TAB completion)

  File spec: [user]drive:filename.ext
  Wildcards: * and ? supported in source
  Dest "." means current drive and user
  TAB completes filenames in interactive mode

  Options:
    /V  Verify after copy
    /C  Confirm each file
    /R  Replace existing without prompt
    /Q  Quiet mode

  Examples:
    SCOPY *.COM B:
    SCOPY [0]A:FILE.TXT [3]B:
    SCOPY FOO.COM B:BAR.COM


5. VALIDATION AND PRE-FLIGHT CHECKS
----------------------------------------------------------------

All validation occurs BEFORE any file data is copied.

5.1. Command Line Parsing

  - Parse source and destination file specifications.
  - Validate user numbers are in range 0-15.
  - Validate drive letters are A-P.
  - Validate filenames conform to 8.3 format:
    - Filename: 1-8 characters.
    - Extension: 0-3 characters (period required if extension
      is present).
    - Valid characters: A-Z, 0-9, and the following special
      characters: ! # $ & ' @ ^ ` { } ~ ( ) - _
    - Invalid characters: < > . , ; : = ? * [ ] | \
      (Note: * and ? are valid in source only as wildcards)
    - Filenames are converted to uppercase.
  - If wildcards are used in the source and a destination
    filename is specified (not just drive/user), error:
    "Rename not allowed with wildcards"
  - If source and destination resolve to the same drive,
    user area, AND filename — error:
    "Cannot copy file to itself"

5.2. Source File Validation

  - Set the source user area via BDOS function 32.
  - Search for source files using BDOS functions 17/18
    (Search First / Search Next).
  - If no files match, error: "No matching files"
  - Expand wildcard matches into a file list.
  - Calculate total size of all source files in kilobytes
    by examining the extent and record count fields of all
    directory entries for each file.

5.3. Destination Capacity Checks

  - Set the destination user area.
  - Select the destination drive.
  - Use BDOS function 46 (Get Disk Free Space) or calculate
    free space from the allocation vector (BDOS function 27)
    and the Disk Parameter Block (BDOS function 31).
  - Check: total source size <= destination free space.
    If not, error: "Insufficient disk space (need XXK, have XXK)"
  - Calculate the number of directory extents needed:
    For each source file, count its extents (not just one
    entry per file — large files span multiple extents).
    Compare against free directory entries on the destination.
    If insufficient, error:
    "Insufficient directory space (need XX, have XX free)"

5.4. Self-Copy Detection

  For each file in the expanded source list, verify that the
  fully resolved destination (drive + user + filename) does
  not match the fully resolved source. This check must account
  for defaults — if the user omits the drive from the
  destination, it defaults to the current drive, which may be
  the same as the source drive.

5.5. Existing File Detection

  For each destination file, check if it already exists:
  - Default behavior: prompt "Overwrite FILENAME.EXT? (Y/N)"
  - With /R flag: overwrite without prompting
  - If user answers N: skip that file and continue with the
    next file in the wildcard list.


6. COPY OPERATION
----------------------------------------------------------------

6.1. Buffer Strategy

  SCOPY uses all available TPA memory above its own code and
  data as a file buffer. The buffer extends from the end of
  the program's data area to the base of the BDOS (address
  obtained from location 0006H-0007H minus a safety margin).

  For each file:
    1. Set source user area and drive.
    2. Open the source file (BDOS function 15).
    3. Read as many 128-byte records as fit in the buffer
       (BDOS function 20, sequential read).
    4. Set destination user area and drive.
    5. If first pass, create/open destination file
       (BDOS function 22, Make File / function 15, Open).
    6. Write buffered records to destination
       (BDOS function 21, sequential write).
    7. If source file is not fully read, repeat from step 1
       (multi-pass for files larger than buffer).
    8. Close destination file (BDOS function 16).
    9. Close source file (BDOS function 16).

  If a write error occurs (BDOS returns non-zero from
  function 21), abort immediately with error:
  "Write error on FILENAME.EXT — copy aborted"

  If a read error occurs (BDOS returns non-zero and non-EOF
  from function 20), abort immediately with error:
  "Read error on FILENAME.EXT — copy aborted"

6.2. File Attributes

  After a successful copy, the destination file should have
  the same attributes (R/O, SYS, Archive) as the source.
  Attributes are read from the source directory entry and
  applied to the destination using BDOS function 30
  (Set File Attributes).

  If the destination file already exists and is marked R/O:
  - Default behavior: display "FILENAME.EXT is Read-Only,
    overwrite? (Y/N)"
  - With /R flag: temporarily clear R/O, overwrite, then
    set attributes to match source.

6.3. Verify Pass (/V flag)

  After writing and closing the destination file:
    1. Reopen both source and destination files.
    2. Read both files one buffer-load at a time.
    3. Compare the buffers byte-for-byte.
    4. If mismatch found, error:
       "Verify failed on FILENAME.EXT"
    5. Close both files.

6.4. Confirm Mode (/C flag)

  Before copying each file in a wildcard expansion, prompt:
    "Copy FILENAME.EXT? (Y/N) "
  If N, skip the file. If Y, proceed with the copy.
  The pre-flight space calculation is performed on ALL
  matching files before any prompts are shown. Files skipped
  by the user simply result in less space being used.


7. DISPLAY OUTPUT
----------------------------------------------------------------

7.1. Normal Mode

  SCOPY v1.0

  Source: [3]A:*.COM (5 files, 48K)
  Dest:   [5]B:     (112K free, 38 dir entries free)

  Copying STAT.COM ...OK
  Copying PIP.COM ...OK
  Copying DUMP.COM ...OK
  Copying ASM.COM ...OK
  Copying LOAD.COM ...OK

  5 file(s) copied, 48K transferred

7.2. With /V Flag

  Copying STAT.COM ...OK, Verified
  Copying PIP.COM ...OK, Verified

7.3. With /C Flag

  Copy STAT.COM? (Y/N) Y
  Copying STAT.COM ...OK
  Copy PIP.COM? (Y/N) N
  Skipping PIP.COM

7.4. With /Q Flag

  Only the header and summary lines are displayed.
  Per-file lines are suppressed.

7.5. Error Output

  Errors are displayed on the console and the program
  terminates with a warm boot (JMP 0000H).

  SCOPY v1.0

  Error: Insufficient disk space (need 96K, have 64K)


8. PROGRAM STRUCTURE (8080 ASSEMBLY)
----------------------------------------------------------------

8.1. Module Layout

  The program should be organized into these logical sections:

  MAIN      — Entry point, parse command line, orchestrate
  PARSE     — Command line parser, file spec extraction
  VALID     — Validation routines (filename, self-copy, etc.)
  DIR       — Directory search, wildcard expansion, file list
  SPACE     — Free space and directory entry calculations
  COPY      — File read/write/verify buffer management
  TABCOMP   — TAB completion line editor, match cycling
  DISPLAY   — Console output routines, number formatting
  DATA      — FCBs, buffers, variables, string constants

8.2. Key Data Structures

  Source FCB (36 bytes) — For source file operations
  Destination FCB (36 bytes) — For destination file operations
  File List — Table of matched filenames from wildcard search
    Each entry: 11 bytes (8 filename + 3 extension)
    Maximum entries: limited by available memory, but a
    practical limit of 128 files per wildcard is reasonable.
  Copy Buffer — From end of data area to BDOS base
  TAB Match List — Up to 64 entries of 11 bytes each (704 bytes)
    for TAB completion cycling. Stored within the data area.
  Line Input Buffer — For interactive mode line editing,
    up to 128 bytes.

8.3. BDOS Functions Used

  0   — System Reset (warm boot on fatal error)
  1   — Console Input (for Y/N prompts)
  2   — Console Output (character output)
  6   — Direct Console I/O (for TAB completion input)
  9   — Print String (terminated by '$')
  12  — Return Version Number (verify CP/M 2.2)
  13  — Reset Disk System
  14  — Select Disk
  15  — Open File
  16  — Close File
  17  — Search for First
  18  — Search for Next
  19  — Delete File (before overwriting)
  20  — Read Sequential
  21  — Write Sequential
  22  — Make File (create new file)
  25  — Return Current Disk
  27  — Get Addr(Alloc Vector)
  31  — Get Addr(Disk Parameter Block)
  32  — Set/Get User Code
  35  — Compute File Size (for size calculation)

8.4. Command Line Access

  The CP/M CCP places the command tail (everything after
  the command name) at address 0080H, with the character
  count at 0080H and the text starting at 0081H. The tail
  is uppercase and space-delimited.

8.5. Memory Map

  0000H-0007H   Warm boot vector, IOBYTE, current drive
  0080H-00FFH   Command tail / default DMA buffer
  0100H         Program start (ORG 100H)
  xxxxH         End of program code and data
  xxxxH         Start of copy buffer
  xxxxH         BDOS base (from address 0006H-0007H)


9. ERROR MESSAGES
----------------------------------------------------------------

  "Type SCOPY /? for help"
  "Invalid source file specification"
  "Invalid destination file specification"
  "Invalid filename character: x"
  "Filename too long (8.3 max)"
  "Invalid user number (0-15)"
  "Invalid drive letter"
  "No matching files"
  "Rename not allowed with wildcards"
  "Cannot copy file to itself"
  "Insufficient disk space (need XXK, have XXK)"
  "Insufficient directory space (need XX, have XX free)"
  "File is Read-Only: FILENAME.EXT"
  "Read error on FILENAME.EXT"
  "Write error on FILENAME.EXT"
  "Verify failed on FILENAME.EXT"
  "Cannot create file: FILENAME.EXT"
  "Cannot open file: FILENAME.EXT"


10. LIMITATIONS AND NOTES
----------------------------------------------------------------

  - Maximum user area: 15 (CP/M 2.2 standard)
  - Maximum file size: 8MB (65536 x 128-byte records)
  - Maximum files per wildcard match: 128 (practical limit)
  - Maximum TAB completion matches: 64 (circular cycling)
  - Filename matching is case-insensitive (all converted
    to uppercase per CP/M convention)
  - Submit files (*.SUB) can be used to script SCOPY
    commands for batch operations.
  - SCOPY requires CP/M 2.2 or compatible. It uses BDOS
    function 32 (user code) which is not available in
    CP/M 1.4.
  - Files larger than available TPA memory are handled
    transparently by the multi-pass buffer strategy.
  - Drive/user state is restored to the original values
    before program exit (warm boot handles this, but
    explicit restore is done for clean operation).


11. BUILD PROCEDURE
----------------------------------------------------------------

  Assemble:   M80 =SCOPY
              (produces SCOPY.REL)
  Link:       L80 SCOPY,SCOPY/N/E
              (produces SCOPY.COM)


12. FUTURE CONSIDERATIONS (NOT IN v1.0)
----------------------------------------------------------------

  These features are explicitly out of scope for v1.0
  but noted for potential future versions:

  - Date/time stamp preservation (requires CP/M 3.0 or
    DateStamper)
  - Archive bit-based incremental copy (/A flag)
  - Interactive mode for browsing and selecting files
  - Directory display mode (list matching files without
    copying)

